ElementDescription: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
Subject ID how it's defined in lab/project
Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
Age in months at the time of the interview/test/sampling/imaging.
Notes: Age is rounded to chronological month. If the research participant is 15-days-old at time of interview, the appropriate value would be 0 months. If the participant is 16-days-old, the value would be 1 month.
M = Male; F = Female; O=Other; NR = Not reported
Total number of words in text

ElementDescription: True averaged Edinburgh Postnatal Depression Scale score for a given text-EPDS pair
Notes: Higher score is more indicative of postnatal depression.

ElementDescription: Predicted Edinburgh Postnatal Depression Scale value based off of modeling with only demographic features
Notes: 999=NA; Higher score is more indicative of postnatal depression. If any of the variables are missing, then the data point was not included in the model and did not receive an EPDS score.

ElementDescription: Predicted Edinburgh Postnatal Depression Scale value based off of modeling with demographic features and NLP features
Notes: 999=NA; Higher score is more indicative of postnatal depression. If any of the variables are missing, then the data point was not included in the model and did not receive an EPDS score.

ElementDescription: Predicted Edinburgh Postnatal Depression Scale value based off of modeling with demographic features, NLP features, mood, and symptoms
Notes: 999=NA; Higher score is more indicative of postnatal depression. If any of the variables are missing, then the data point was not included in the model and did not receive an EPDS score.

ElementDescription: Average number of words per sentence
Percent of words that are captured by LIWC

Percent of words that are in any of the LIWC linguistic dimension categories (pronouns, articles, numbers, prepositions, auxiliary verbs, adverbs, conjunctions, negations, common verbs, common adjectives, and quantities)
Percent of words that are determiners (the, at, that, my, etc.)
Percent of words that are quantities (all, one, more, some, etc.)
Percent of words that are related to cognition (is, was, but, are, etc.)
Percent of words that are related to all-or-none thinking (all, no, never, always, etc.)
Percent of words that are related to memory (remember, forgot, remind, amnesia, etc.)
Percent of words that measure affect, emotion, and swear words (good, injustice, new, love, etc.)
Percent of words that have a positive tone (important, yay, birthday, reliable, etc.)
Percent of words that have a negative tone (bad, wrong, too much, hate, etc.)
Percent of words that demonstrate emotion (hope, wronged, insecure, comfortable, etc.)
Percent of words that are related to social behavior (said, love, say, care, etc.)
Percent of words that are prosocial behavior (care, help, thank, please, etc.)
Percent of words that indicate politeness (thank, please, good morning, pardon, etc.)
Percent of words that are related to interpersonal conflict (fight, kill, attack, nemesis, etc.)

Notes: Example: 30-day LASSO model with demographics and NLP features

ElementDescription: Percent of words that are related to moralization (wrong, honor, deserve, judge, etc.)
Percent of words that are related to communication (said, say, tell, thank, etc.)
Percent of words that are social referents (boyfriend, human, mamma, yall, etc.)
Percent of words that are related to culture, i.e. politics, ethnicity, and technology (car, united states, government, phone, etc.)

Percent of words that are ethnicities (American, French, Chinese, Indian, etc.)
Percent of words that are related to technology (car, phone, computer, email, etc.)
Percent of words that are related to lifestyle (work, home, school, fun, etc.)
Percent of words that are related to physical health and physical experiences (medical, food, patients, eye, etc.)
Percent of words that are related to physical health (respiratory, anemia, rehab, seizure, etc.)
Numerical label for text-EPDS (Edinburgh Postnatal Depression Scale) pair or data point going into the model
Percent of words that are related to illness (hospital, cancer, sick, pain, etc.)
Percent of words that are related to wellness (healthy, gym, supported, diet, etc.)
Percent of words that are related to mental health (depressed, suicide, trauma, zoloft, etc.)
Percent of words that are related to substances (beer, wine, drunk, cigar, etc.)
Percent of words that are related to food (dietary, drink, eat dinner, etc.)
Percent of words that are related to the state of need (have to, need, must, crisis, etc.)
Percent of words that are related to the state of wanting (want, hope, wished, crave, etc.)
Percent of words that are related to acquiring (accumulate, get, take, robbed, etc.)
Percent of words that are related to lacking (less, don''t have, absent, scarce, etc.)
Percent of words that are related to fulfillment (enough, full, complete, extra, etc.)
The group that the participant has been assigned to for modeling
Percent of words that are related to fatigue (tired, bored, don''t care, sleepy, etc.)
Percent of words that are related to curiosity (science, looking for, research, wonder, etc.)
Percent of words that are related to allure (have, like, out, know, etc.)
Percent of words that are related to attention (look, watch, check, warning, etc.)
Percent of words that are conversational (yeah, oh, yes, okay, etc.)

ElementDescription: Average mood recorded in the app's daily check-in feature during the 30-day or 60-day time period in which journal entries are eligible.

ElementDescription: Binary variable for whether or not the patient reported symptoms in the 30-day or 60-day time period in which journal entries are eligible.
